Paracuellos is a work of great courage, created at a time when telling the truth about Spain's political past could get one killed. It is arguably the most important graphic memoir ever created in comics. Carlos Gim√©nez‚Äôs autobiographical account of the plight of children in post-World War II Fascist Spain has won virtually every comics award in Europe, including ‚ÄúBest Album‚Äù at the 1981 Angoul√™me Festival, and the ‚ÄúHeritage Award‚Äù at Angoul√™me in 2010.

In the late 1930s when Spanish fascists led by Franco, and aided by Hitler and Mussolini, overthrew the elected government, almost 200,000 men and women fell in battle, were executed, or died in prison. Their orphaned children‚Äîand others ripped from the homes of the defeated‚Äîwere shuttled from Church-run ‚Äúhome‚Äù to ‚Äúhome‚Äù and fed a steady diet of torture and disinformation by a totalitarian state bent on making them ‚Äúproductive‚Äù citizens. Carlos Gim√©nez was one of those children. In 1975, after Franco‚Äôs death, Carlos began to tell his story. Breaking the code of silence proved to be a milestone, both for the comics medium and for a country coming to terms with its past.

An illustrated essay by Carmen Moreno-Nu√±o, Associate Professor of Hispanic Studies at the University of Kentucky, places the comics in historical perspective.
name: Children of the Defeated In Franco's Fascist Spain

Do you love networking to advance your career? Is adulthood an exciting new challenge for which you feel fully prepared? Ugh. Please go away.

These casually drawn, perfectly on-point comics by the hugely popular young Brooklyn-based artist Sarah Andersen are for the rest of us. They document the wasting of entire beautiful weekends on the internet, the unbearable agony of holding hands on the street with a gorgeous guy, and dreaming all day of getting home and back into pajamas. In other words, the horrors and awkwardnesses of young modern life. Oh and they are totally not autobiographical. At all.

Adulthood Is a Myth presents many fan favorites plus dozens of all-new comics exclusive to this book. Like the work of fellow Millennial authors Allie Brosh, Grace Helbig, and Gemma Correll, Sarah's frankness on personal issues like body image, self-consciousness, introversion, relationships, and the frequency of bra-washing makes her comics highly relatable and deeply hilarious.

Note: The digital edition (3/8/2016) for this volume was released before the print edition.
